<br>
As for Rome....yes, that's why it's the dark ages of europe.....<br>
<br>
The romans had it going on if not in swords, in almost everything else.. The gladus was made from bronze..... I'll refain from saying why bronze sucks but hey they used it ok.<br>
<br>
The germans and all were barbarians you know. Don;t be fooled that the barbarians own the world now and like to pretty up their past.  Rise and fall of the great powers - Paul Kennedy is a great book for a econ centered view of the world from 1500's to WWII (after that its not really history any more).<br>
<br>
Bottom line is that America was non existant in 1500 and western Europe was a pack of cave men that had just survived about 25%-50% of their population getting destroyed in a most greusome way ala the plague (prolly more like 50%).<br>
<br>
So 1500's you had a new spark lit under europe, those that lived could be considered God's chosen if they squinted and they could go back to their favorite past time... killing their neighbors.<br>
<br>
so europe was this super fragmented village with sharp sticks mentality such that any one self styled lord couldn't lay real claim to large areas and if they made stupid tarrifs, the growing merchant classes would just skip their county and do business elsewhere.<br>
<br>
Civilization was to the east, nothing to see in europe.<br>
<br>
<br>
So the costal europeans (the dutch notably and spain/portugal) invent fun kinds of boats that can take rough waters unlike the gallys the rest of the world was using. <br>
<br>
That meant lots of weird pale people running around in places they'd never been seen before....<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.iisg.nl/exhibitions/japaneseprints/ships.html">www.iisg.nl/exhibitions/j...ships.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
That combined with trade from the bizantines filtered gunpowder to europe. Oh my how europe took that and ran with it.<br>
<br>
So following me so far?<br>
<br>
Gunpower + boats =&gt; colonialism!<br>
<br>
so europe hit the americas and african coasts and started small and working form there.  The spanish hit it big in southern america for a combination of exceedingly asute leadership and that the natives HATED HATED the aztecs. Lot of fun exploitaion going on there.<br>
<br>
So as time wore on and europe was now a pack of  larger villages who had replaced their 'sharpsticks' with 'guns and sharpsticks'!!! They were constantly striving for better guns to replace the sharpsticks.<br>
<br>
The 'rest' of the Civilized World sat back and were clueless. I mean assuming Europe was civilized yet...the rest of the world certainly didn;t think so.<br>
<br>
so time went on and if you enjoy european history you get to discover names like Moltke and needlegun and Franco-Prussian.<br>
<br>
The watershed was about 1880's when a man named Maxim decided to give up on incandesant lightbulbs and work on a self sustaining machinegun.<br>
<br>
The gatling gun was a sort of hand cranked thing that was prone to failure. So yes it was a machinegun but no, from a military viewpoint, it was a joke.<br>
<br>
So The american inventor moved to england and set up shop. Hiram Maxim tackled a problem lots of other people were working on at the same time... how to make it automatic... That is what a machine gun is really about.<br>
<br>
so 1885 maxim invented a means to use some of the power of the shot to eject the now empty cartridge and load in a fresh one. The gun could be turned on and the gun would go though the entire belt of ammo eventually. The gunner steered the gun and the assitant linked more belts =p<br>
<br>
The prototype fired 500 rounds a minute.<br>
<br>
So the 30 years leading up to WWI (the war to end all wars) England and the rest used this new toy to make their colonialism even more pronounced. 'Famed' instances of 50 men beating off 5000 natives and all from this remarkable tool. After odds like that no one in their right mind would uprise.<br>
<br>
So maxim invented the first real machine gun as we know it. To be honest there's really not much else to improve on from the original maxim to a modern machinegun.... it's all evolutionary.<br>
<br>
<br>
As for firebombings... dresden.. Yup The US helped the english there, The resulting firestorm wasn;t really intended but then again one questions bombing civilians.<br>
<br>
The US really put the hammer to Japan using incendiarys to the point where the raw loss of life and overall damage was far greater than the nuclear weapons. The idea wasn;t to hurt industry, but the people that worked in the factories... in that regard it worked all too well. The only reason General Curtis Lemay stopped firebombing was because he ran out of incendiary munitions...... There's a saying about warcriminals only seem to occur on the losing side...<br>
<br>
All in all, America is the child of europe and share the same sort of mindset regarding so many things look at how the native north americans fared. <br>
<br>
Oh and nothing was mass produced all those years... just that pollaxes were REALLY dirt cheap to make. A disposable weapon for the field, when it came time to say hi to that ladies they got the swords out.<br>
<br>
Oh and yes spain made some nice swords but that is also a combination of too little too late and a whole lot of hype =)<br>
<br>
Cheers!<br>
-Liq<br>
